# Step 1: Creating the VPC

This is done by inputting a custom name for your VPC.
Next step is to configure the settings to the following:
IPv4 CIDR- 10.0.0.0/16, No IPv6 CIDR, Tenancy= Default

# Step 2: Create the Public Subnet

Navigate to Subnets and go to Create Subnet.
Configure the settings to the following:
Select a name for the subnet, pick your suitable AZ (Availability Zone), and your CIDR- 10.0.1.0/24
Check settings and then create Subnet.
To enable Auto-Assign Public IP, click on the subnet-Actions-Edit subnet settings.
Tick the box labelled: Enable auto-assign public IPv4 address

# Step 3: Create the Private Subnet

Go back to the Subnets main menu and click on Create Subnet again to create another subnet.
Configure the settings again through the following:
Select a name that can differentiate between the public and private subnet, pick the same AZ, and use the CIDR 10.0.2.0/24
Check the settings and create the Subnet. DO NOT ENABLE AUTO-ASSIGN PUBLIC IP.

# Step 4: Create an Internet Gateway

Navigate to Internet Gateways and click Create Internet Gateway.
Provide a name and click Create.
Once created, click Actions-Attach to VPC.
Attach the VPC you had created.

# Step 5: Create an Elastic IP

Navigate to Elastic IPs.
Click on Allocate Elastic IP address.
Continue with the default settings provided and click Allocate.

# Step 6: Create the NAT Gateway

Navigate to Nat Gateways and click Create NAT Gateway.
Create a name for this.
Under Availability mode: Select Zonal and then the Public Subnet that you created.
Select Public for connectivity type and then select your created Elastic IP.
Double check settings and click Create NAT gateway.
Wait until the state turns to Available.

# Step 7: Create the Public Route Table

Navigate to Route tables and click Create route table.
State a name for the route table, select your VPC and click Create route table.

# Add Internet Route

Navigate to Routes-Edit Routes and then select Add route.
Destination= 0.0.0.0/0, Target= Internet Gateway then select your IGW.
Click Save changes.

# Associate Public Subnet

Navigate to Subnet associations and then click Edit subnet associations.
Select the Public Subnet you created and then click Save associations.

# Step 8: Create the Private Route Table

Navigate back to route tables and create another route table.
Give this a name to differentiate from the Public Route Table.

# Add NAT Route

Go to Edit Routes and Add route.
Destination= 0.0.0.0/0, Target= NAT Gateway then select your NGW.
Click Save changes.

# Associate Private Subnet

Navigate to Subnet associations and then click Edit subnet associations.
Select the Private Subnet you created and then click Save associations.

# Step 9: Create Security Groups

Navigate to Security groups and click Create security group.
Add a suitable name for the group, connect your vpc and then the following configuration:
Inbound rules: Type= SSH       Source= My IP      Type= HTTP     Source= My IP
Outbound rules: Keep as default.
Click Create security group.

Create another private security group. Settings are as follows:
Inbound rules: Type=SSH        Source= Public SG that I created before this one.
This allows only instances in that security group to connect.
Outbound rules: Keep as default.
Click Create security group.

# Step 10: Launch Public EC2

Navigate to EC2-Instances-Launch Instances.
Configure the settings to the following:
Use a custom name
AMI= Amazon Linux 2023, Instance type= t3.micro  Key pair= Either create a new one or use existing, select your VPC
Subnet= Public Subnet that you created earlier, Auto-assign public IP= Enable, Security Group= Public SG.
Launch instance.

# Step 11: Launch Private EC2

Launch another instance with the following settings:
Same AMI and Instance type and Key pair as the public EC2.
Select your created VPC, Subnet= Private Subnet that was created, Auto-assign public IP= Disable, Security Group= Private SG
Launch instance.

# Step 12: Test Connectivity

SSH from your device using the following command: ssh -i mykey.pem ec2-user@<Public-IP>
Should successfully connect.

# Bonus Step: Enable Cloudwatch

Go to your Instance and select: Actions- Monitor and Troubleshoot.
Install the Cloudwatch Agent and then check the metrics on the Monitoring tab.

